Titanic

1 Introduction

This dataset is from Kaggles machine learning project based where participants are to predict if passengers survived or not. It requires feature engineering, missing value correction, outlier correction, and random forests to come up with a model.

1.1 Loading libraries

library(data.table)

2 Exploration

2.1 Visual exploration

Sometimes looking at numbers doesnt tell the whole story. Lets start with some visuals.

#Create a function to be able to visualize tables and bar charts
vis1 <- function(feat){
  temp.table <- table(titanic[[feat]], titanic$Survived)
  print(temp.table)
  
  ggplot(titanic, aes_string(x = feat)) +
    geom_bar(aes(fill = Survived)) +
    theme_few() +
    guides(fill = guide_legend(reverse=TRUE)) +
    ylab("") +
    xlab("") +
    ggtitle(paste(feat))
}

#Create a function to be able to visualize proportions and stacked bar charts
vis2 <- function(feat){
  prop.temp  <- as.data.frame(prop.table(table(titanic[[feat]], titanic$Survived),1))
  print(prop.temp)
  
  ggplot(prop.temp, aes(x = Var1, y = Freq, fill = Var2)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    theme_few() +
    guides(fill = guide_legend(reverse=TRUE)) +
    ylab("") +
    xlab("") +
    ggtitle(paste(feat)) +
    scale_fill_discrete(name="Survived")
}

3.2 Imputation

We need to fill in the information. Currently we know that the passenger is a female, 80 fare, and 1st class. We will create a boxplot to get similar cases of this passenger and plugin the median fare.

#graph and hline at 80
ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Pclass, y = Fare, fill = Pclass)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_grid(~Embarked, scales = "free") +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept=80)) +
  theme_few() +
  scale_fill_few() +
  xlab("") +
  ylab("") +
  ggtitle("Medians of fares for Embarks")

titanic[, .(median = median(Fare)), by = .(Embarked, Pclass)][order(Embarked)]

It looks like the user is similarly grouped at embarkment C based on the median fare. Lets plug it in.

titanic$Embarked[titanic$Embarked == ""] <- "C"

3.4 Feature engineering

#use feature engineering to find missing values of age. Let's extract titles from passenger's names
titanic$Title <- gsub('(.*, )|(\\..*)', '', titanic$Name)

#using wikipedia they define the title master as a boy younger than 16. Trying to fill in NAs for age 
#will prove difficult unless we use a predictive model since NA ages include females that do not have a 
#corresponding term for younger than 16.

#verification
titanic[is.na(Age), .(Title, Name, Sex, Age)]

We will need to extract more useful information out of our data if we want to make a good model.

4.2 Cabin numbers

Depending on where the cabin is located perhaps the passenger has a higher rate of survival

#Cabin feature creation. $First letter
head(titanic$Cabin, 10)
##  [1] ""     "C85"  ""     "C123" ""     ""     "E46"  ""     ""     ""
titanic[, Cab.Letter := substr(Cabin, 1,1)]

titanic$Cab.Letter[titanic$Cab.Letter == ""] <- "Unknown"

#1 digit number
titanic[, Cabin.1digit := ifelse(nchar(Cabin) == 2, 1, 0)]

#2 digit number
titanic[, Cabin.2digit := ifelse(nchar(Cabin) == 3, 1, 0)]

#3 digit number
titanic[, Cabin.3digit := ifelse(nchar(Cabin) == 4, 1, 0)]

#multiple rooms 
titanic[, Cabin.Multiple := ifelse(nchar(Cabin) > 4, 1, 0)]

5 RandomForest

Now that we have numerous features, we must now prepare to train and test our model

#Set up factors for randomForest
titanic$Title <- as.factor(titanic$Title)
titanic$Cab.Letter <- as.factor(titanic$Cab.Letter)
titanic$Cabin.1digit <- as.factor(titanic$Cabin.1digit)
titanic$Cabin.2digit <- as.factor(titanic$Cabin.2digit)
titanic$Cabin.3digit <- as.factor(titanic$Cabin.3digit)
titanic$Cabin.Multiple <- as.factor(titanic$Cabin.Multiple)

5.1 Splitting our data

Well use the package Caret to split our training data to 85% of the data and use the remaining 15% for testing.

#Set up training and test data set
set.seed(2)
split <- createDataPartition(titanic$Survived, p = .85, list = FALSE)

training <- titanic[split,]
testing <- titanic[-split,]

nrow(training) 
## [1] 758
nrow(testing)
## [1] 133

5.2 Creating our model

Not shown here: iterative feature selection testing. The best combination are the following.

#Create model
m1 <- randomForest(Survived ~ Pclass + Sex + Fare + Fam.Five + Title + 
                    Cabin.2digit, data = training, importance = TRUE)

5.4 Testing our model

#Test model 
p1 <- predict(m1, testing)

5.5 Results

There were 19 incorrect predictions against 104 which gives us our accuracy below.

table(testing$Survived, p1)
